# 2.2 Reference strategy 

A common practice in order execution brokerage is that clients may come forward to brokers with their own preferred strategies for benchmarking. These benchmark strategies can be either strategies suggested by elite investors or commonly used ones such as TWAP strategies. We shall refer to these pre-specified benchmark strategies as reference strategies. We consider the reference strategies that can be represented by a deterministic function $\left(R_{t}\right)_{t \in[0, T]}$ with $R_{0} \equiv x_{0}$ and $R_{T} \equiv A$ hereafter. Moreover, we assume that $R_{t}$ is a differentiable a.e. function. The broker's incentive of executing client's order is thus to maximize his own expected $\mathrm{P} \& \mathrm{~L}$ excess to that of the reference strategy, marked-to-market. Specifically, by disregarding the price impact and slippages incurred from order execution, the stock price $S_{t}^{0}$ reads

$$
S_{t}^{0}=S_{0}+\mu t+\sigma W_{t}
$$

The marked-to-market $\mathrm{P} \& \mathrm{~L} \Pi^{R}$ for the reference strategy $R$ is evaluated as

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Pi^{R} & :=\int_{0}^{T}\left(-S_{t}^{0}\right) \mathrm{d} R_{t} \\
& =-\left(S_{t}^{0} R_{t}\right) \int_{0}^{T}+\int_{0}^{T} R_{t}\left(\mu \mathrm{~d} t+\sigma \mathrm{d} W_{t}\right) \\
& =-A S_{T}^{0}+x_{0} S_{0}+\int_{0}^{T} \mu R_{t} \mathrm{~d} t+\int_{0}^{T} \sigma R_{t} \mathrm{~d} W_{t} \\
& =\left(x_{0}-A\right) S_{0}+\int_{0}^{T} \mu\left(R_{t}-A\right) \mathrm{d} t+\int_{0}^{T} \sigma\left(R_{t}-A\right) \mathrm{d} W_{t}
\end{aligned}
$$

Hence, the broker's excess $\mathrm{P} \& \mathrm{~L} \tilde{\Pi}$, defined by the difference between $\Pi$ and $\Pi^{R}$, is given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\tilde{\Pi}:= & \Pi-\Pi^{R} \\
= & -\beta\left(x_{T}-A\right)^{2}+\int_{0}^{T}\left(\mu\left(x_{t}-R_{t}\right)+\rho \sigma m\left(v_{t}\right)-\eta v_{t}^{2}-\gamma v_{t}\left(x_{t}-A\right)\right) \mathrm{d} t \\
& +\int_{0}^{T} \sigma\left(x_{t}-R_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} W_{t}+\int_{0}^{T}\left(\eta v_{t}+\gamma\left(x_{t}-A\right)\right) m\left(v_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} Z_{t}
\end{aligned}
$$

The broker's goal is thus to maximize his expected excess $\mathrm{P} \& \mathrm{~L}$ in a risk aversion manner which we recast as a utility maximization problem in the section that follows.

## A Appendix
## A. 1 Proof to Proposition 1

By Itô's formula,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left(x_{T}-A\right) S_{T}= & \left(x_{0}-A\right) S_{0}+\int_{0}^{T} S_{t} \mathrm{~d} x_{t}+\int_{0}^{T}\left(\mu\left(x_{t}-A\right)+\rho \sigma m\left(v_{t}\right)-\gamma v_{t}\left(x_{t}-A\right)\right) \mathrm{d} t \\
& +\int_{0}^{T} \sigma\left(x_{t}-A\right) \mathrm{d} W_{t}+\int_{0}^{T} \gamma\left(x_{t}-A\right) m\left(v_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} Z_{t}
\end{aligned}
$$

Furthermore, note that $\tilde{S}_{t}=S_{t}+\eta v_{t}$,

$$
\int_{0}^{T}\left(-\tilde{S}_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} x_{t}=-\int_{0}^{T} S_{t} \mathrm{~d} x_{t}-\int_{0}^{T} \eta v_{t}^{2} \mathrm{~d} t+\int_{0}^{T} \eta v_{t} m\left(v_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} Z_{t}
$$

in summary,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Pi= & \left(x_{T}-A\right) S_{T}-\beta\left(x_{T}-A\right)^{2}+\int_{0}^{T}\left(-\hat{S}_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} x_{t} \\
= & \left(x_{0}-A\right) S_{0}-\beta\left(x_{T}-A\right)^{2}+\int_{0}^{T}\left(\mu\left(x_{t}-A\right)+\rho \sigma m\left(v_{t}\right)-\eta v_{t}^{2}-\gamma v_{t}\left(x_{t}-A\right)\right) \mathrm{d} t \\
& +\int_{0}^{T} \sigma\left(x_{t}-A\right) \mathrm{d} W_{t}+\int_{0}^{T}\left(\eta v_{t}+\gamma\left(x_{t}-A\right)\right) m\left(v_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} Z_{t}
\end{aligned}
$$

